Why the chronological anthology is the right pick
- Match with archival priorities: The anthology explicitly preserves tape warmth, wide dynamics and instrument separation — this directly addresses my preference for original‑mix archival sound and spacious imaging. That preservation is far more important to my listening goals than a glossy rework or shortened radio edits.
- Chronological sequencing and liner‑note context: The candidate is a chronological anthology with deliberate sequencing, rarities and alternate takes plus rich liner notes. That structure supports start‑to‑finish, album‑oriented listening and deep‑cut discovery — exactly the experience I prize over a front‑loaded hits package.
- Minimal editorial interference and nuance: The presence of alternate takes and rarities implies an archival, collector mindset rather than heavy remixing or truncation. The emphasis on instrument separation and wide dynamics indicates the mastering will reveal layered interplay and shifting arrangements on repeated hi‑fi listens, which aligns with my taste for nuanced, layered listening.
- Heavy material without the muddy downside: While the anthology includes guitar‑forward late‑60s/70s cuts with weighty riffs (Iommi‑style tones), the release is described as remastered for audiophile nuance, not as muddy, jammy Southern‑rock. That distinction matters: I dislike muddy, poorly produced heavy rock, but I do appreciate well‑preserved, robust early heavy/metal tones when they’re presented with good separation and dynamic range — which this anthology promises.
Why I reject the AOR 'Their Greatest Hits' rebuild
- Hit‑collection format and reworking: The AOR release is a greatest‑hits style package “rebuilt” into concise 3–5 minute tracks with tight, front‑loaded sequencing and big singalong choruses. That directly conflicts with my dislike of single‑focused, hit‑forward compilations and anthem/chorus‑driven albums that prioritize instant hooks over album context and archival depth.
- Loss of album‑by‑album context and minimal edits: My stated preference is for minimal edits and album sequencing that reveal extended arrangements and shifting grooves. The AOR set’s concise, radio-friendly reconstructions work against extended or deep listening — they’re optimized for immediate enjoyment rather than nuanced repeat plays.
- Although the AOR mastering is described as glossy yet dynamic with good separation (a technical plus), the musical and editorial intent (greatest hits, singalongs, front‑loaded sequencing) makes it the wrong fit for my archival, album‑oriented priorities.
In short: the chronological anthology aligns closely with my archival, album‑by‑album, wide‑dynamics, liner‑note‑rich listening priorities and avoids the hit‑collection compromises I dislike; the AOR greatest‑hits package, despite competent mastering, is too single‑focused and singalong‑driven to satisfy my stated preferences.

